## Version Control

### What?

When we’ve written code, we’ve created a .py file somewhere in our computer (similar to how you can type up and save a text file) and rewritten over it. However, big projects (and your teacher) require that you somehow keep track of what big edits you make to your project. This is where version control comes in handy. It is basically software that allows you to track edits, revert to previous versions if needed, and work on new features independently using branches.  
A repository is the bundle of branches, commits, and code. It is where **all** parts of your project lives.

### How?

Version control works through *commits* and *branches*.

### What are Commits??

*Commits* are the individual changes to make, like game updates – ‘added user login’ or ‘fixed delete button’.  Any time you finish an update to your code, you should commit (send) your changes.   
For example, if you’ve been working on your website and have added a button, you should commit the changes you’ve made to GitHub. Make sure to name your commits in a way that describes what did you change – you might want to look at a previous version of your code later (especially if you break something).

### What are Branches??

*Branches* are separate versions of your project.   
Imagine you have a team of people making a food ordering app. One person might be working on the login branch, while another person works on the frontend branch. It would be very impractical for both people to be working on (and overwriting) the same file, so they code things separately and then merge their branches.  
For your IA, you will probably have a “main” branch. This exists by default, and is where the “final” code will exist.

### What is “Git”?

Git is the actual software that bundles your edits behind the scenes. It is compatible with a bunch of integrated development environments, or IDEs, which is where you write your code.

### What is “GitHub”?

Think of it as a Google Drive for Git. Remember we said a repository is where all your code lives? A repository can exist locally or online. Ours will be online, on GitHub. We will be making commits to the GitHub repo. If you’re reading this, you’ve already accessed an online repository on GitHub and probably cloned it. Think of it as typing your code, finishing a feature, and then uploading to a sort of Google Drive.
